  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a real issue that affects people who feel their group is stereotyped as less capable in science and math. As a barista who’s curious about the world, I’ve seen how even simple things like a math test can make someone nervous if they think they’re not good at it. When I talk to people who’ve struggled with math or science in school, they often mention feeling like they don’t belong in these fields. It’s not just about being smart—it’s about the fear of confirming a stereotype that they’re not cut out for it. For example, a young woman in my community might avoid taking a physics class because she worries she’ll be the only one who doesn’t get it. This kind of stress can really hurt learning. I believe we should address this by making STEM more welcoming and inclusive. In my town, I’ve seen how a little extra encouragement and support from teachers and mentors can make a big difference. It’s about creating an environment where everyone feels safe to try and fail without judgment. As someone who’s always been interested in understanding people, I think the key is to listen and help others feel valued. If we can reduce the fear of being labeled by stereotypes, more people will step up and contribute to STEM. After all, everyone has something to offer, and we shouldn’t let a few outdated beliefs hold them back.",
